						<h1>2019 Novel Coronavirus Resources  </h1>
						<p><img class="size-full wp-image-23335" src="http://kern.org/wp-content/blogs.dir/4/files/sites/4/2020/01/CoronavirusBanner.jpg" alt="" width="824" height="230" srcset="https://kern.org/wp-content/blogs.dir/4/files/sites/4/2020/01/CoronavirusBanner.jpg 824w, https://kern.org/wp-content/blogs.dir/4/files/sites/4/2020/01/CoronavirusBanner-300x84.jpg 300w, https://kern.org/wp-content/blogs.dir/4/files/sites/4/2020/01/CoronavirusBanner-768x214.jpg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 824px) 100vw, 824px"></p>
<h2><span style="color: #993366;">Resources for essential workers needing childcare</span></h2>
<p>Funds are currently available to support at-risk populations and parents who are essential workers who are needing child care or supervision, utilizing the criteria outlined below. For more information or for child care referrals or payment assistance, please click <strong><a href="http://www.kernchildcare.org">HERE.</a></strong></p>
<div>
<p><strong>At-Risk Populations:</strong></p>
<p>• Children identified as receiving Child Protective Services or at risk of abuse, neglect, or exploitation<br>
• Children eligible through the Emergency Child Care Bridge Program for Foster Children<br>
• Families experiencing homelessness as defined in Section 11434(a)(2) of Title 42 of the <em>United States Code</em>, known as the <em>McKinney-Vento Homeless Assistance Act<br></em>• Children of domestic violence survivors</p>
<p><strong>Essential workers in the following sectors, whose total family income does not exceed the current income eligibility threshold and are not able to work remotely (enroll in the order listed):</strong></p>
<p>• Healthcare / Public Health and Emergency Service sectors<br>
• Food and Agriculture, Teachers, education staff, and providers of early learning and care services including custodial, kitchen staff, and other support staff, Workers supporting critical infrastructure, State and local government workers, Communications and Information Technology IT, Energy, Transportation and Logistics, Critical Manufacturing, Hazardous Materials, Financial Services, and Chemical sectors<br>
• All other fields listed on the Essential Critical Infrastructure Workers document, located <strong><a href="https://covid19.ca.gov/img/EssentialCriticalInfrastructureWorkers.pdf">HERE.</a>  </strong></p>
<p><strong>Families with children with disabilities or special health care needs whose IEPs and IFSPs include ELC services.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Essential workers listed in #2 above, whose total family income exceeds the current income eligibility threshold and are not able to work remotely.</strong></p>
<hr>
